FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
July 28, 2020



KSHSAA Fall Activities Permitted to Begin

KSHSAA Fall Activities Permitted to Begin As Scheduled

TOPEKA, Kan. - By action of the KSHSAA Executive Board Tuesday, all fall activities will begin as scheduled for the 2020-21 school year. This includes practice and competition.

Local school districts retain the right to modify the start dates for practice or competition based on their local and county health recommendations.

The KSHSAA considerations for fall activities released on July 22 are still in effect.

post_text: As a result of issues related to COVID 19 Rock Hills Jr/Sr High School will not be able to provide School Physicals this year. Kansas State High School Activities Association does still require a physical on the KSHSAA form if a student plans to participate in any sports activities. This physical must be completed and on file at the Jr/Sr High School prior to the first day of sports practice.

post_text:
Rock Hills Summer Youth regret to inform everyone that we will not be having summer ball as usual this year, 2020. Right now, even with the COVID-19 phase out and KDHE guidelines it would still not be possible for all of us to get together safely to play. However, we hope that if/when this all does clear and we can be closer than 6 feet apart we will be able to get some kids together to play at the ball fields. It would just be against our own teams. We cannot give a date or time of when that will be as it is undetermined and we know that most families will want to go and do when the time comes so we do not want to intrude on that time either.
When you return items back to school next week there will be an envelope with your children’s summer ball dues for you to pick up. If you would prefer the money be kept for 2021 season you can leave it at the school, and I will pick it up and mark your children down as paid for the 2021 season. Thank you all.

Please stay safe! We look forward to next year and hopefully some later this summer.

Bobi Fogo
Rock Hills Summer Youth President

post_text: The Rock Hills Jr/Sr High School senior class presented Jewell County Helping Hands Ministries a check for $1,500.00. The seniors were saving the money for a "senior" trip this spring. COVID 19 made those plans not possible. As a result, the class decided to donate their funds to the Jewell County Helping Hands Ministries. Cathy Dauner, a representative from Helping Hands, received the $1,500 from Sara Tadefa, a senior from Rock Hills High School.

Kansas State Department of Education
April 17 at 4:46 PM ·

We are excited to announce that Kansas teachers, students and parents just got a new partner in their continuous learning efforts.

Thanks to the support of Kansas Public Broadcasters, Kansas students will receive supplemental education content by way of a new television program produced by Kansas PBS stations and KSDE, and hosted by local teachers. The new program called Learning Across Kansas will begin airing the week of April 20.

Each 30-minute segment, individually produced for elementary, middle school and high school students, will feature grade-specific educational content delivered by our very own Kansas teachers who serve on KSDE’s Continuous Learning Task Force.

Teachers, students and parents/caregivers, tune in for short, fun and engaging lessons. Plus, you just might see one of your own teachers presenting!

Learn more by visiting, https://www.ksde.org/Agency/Fiscal-and-Administrative-Services/Communications-and-Recognition-Programs/Learning-Across-Kansas

post_text: Under the guidance of KSDE and the Jewell County Health Department, Rock Hills Schools will continue with meal distribution and the pick-up of students' personal items on Monday, March 30. When participating in either of these events, remember we must strictly adhere to the social distancing requirements of no more than 10 people in any general area and keeping distances of at least 6 feet apart. As a reminder, meals will be distributed daily and you must sign up the day before by 5:00pm if you would like to get a meal for your child aged 1-18. Meals may only be picked up by the child or a parent/guardian.

Important information from the Kansas Department of Education:

Students who miss more than 10% of school days for any reason are less likely to be on grade level in elementary school and less likely to graduate on time. By middle school, chronic absenteeism is a better predictor of on-time graduation than test scores. It’s hard to establish relationships with students who aren’t in class. The best interventions can’t work if students aren’t there to utilize them.

Rock Hills Junior High School competed well at the Beloit Junior High Scholars Bowl Tournament February 20th. There were 9 teams competing. The 8th Grade team was made up of Hannah Simmelink, Cooper Rhea, Mason McMains, Bella Volker, Abbey Schleifer, Matthew Rice and Cody Cleary. Matthew Rice and Cody Cleary both 7th graders competed on the 8th Grade team due to the large number of 6th and 7th Graders. The 8th Grade Team won Second Place Medals. This is the last meet of the season for the 8th Graders.
Rock Hills had 10 students competing on the 7th Grade Team. Rock Hills 7th Grade Team was made up of Jada Eilert, Bethany Simmelink, Gavin Garst, Trinity Ruthstrom, Halle Mizner, Aaron Underwood, Savannah Coil, Faith Reinert, Calen Beck and Ethan Wirth. The team received Second place medals. This was an impressive feat since all members of the team competed in the same number of rounds.

Rock Hills Junior High School competed at the PikeTrail League Scholars Bowl Tournament Feb. 10th, at Downs. There were 11 teams competing. The 8th Grade team was made up of Abbey Schleifer, Cooper Rhea, Hannah Simmelink, Bella Volker and Cody Cleary. The team of Jada Eilert, Gavin Garst, Savannah Coil, Bethany Simmelink, and Halle Mizner won 4 matches. The Rock Hills Junior High Scholar Bowl team next competes at Courtland Feb.18th and Beloit Feb. 20th.

post_text: The Grizzly Boys took on the Lakeside Knights Friday at Downs in a "down to the wire contest". A last second tip in by Rylee Whelchel forced overtime where Rock Hills fell short, 67-68. It was a great game for all to see. The boys are playing their best "team ball" of the year, and it has shown the last few games. The Grizzlies are now 9-5 but look to rebound against Natoma on Tuesday and Lincoln on Friday. We want to thank our loyal fans for coming out to see us play, and we hope to gather more interest as the post season nears. We play off the crowd's energy, and it has certainly helped the last couple games!

It was a great game for all to see. The boys are playing their best "team ball" of the year, and it has shown the last few games. The Grizzlies are now 9-5 but look to rebound against Natoma on Tuesday and Lincoln on Friday. We want to thank our loyal fans for coming out to see us play, and we hope to gather more interest as the post season nears. We play off the crowd's energy, and it has certainly helped the last couple games!

post_text: Rock Hills Junior High School competed at the Smith Center Junior High Scholars Bowl Tournament Feb. 3. There were 10 teams competing. Rock Hills took 16 students to the Round Robin competition. The 8th Grade team was made up of Bella Volker, Cooper Rhea, Abbey Schleifer, Mason McMains, Hannah Simmelink and Matthew Rice. The 8th Grade Team won 8 of their 9 rounds and tied with Thomas Moore Prep and Norton for 1st Place. The 7th Grade Team was made up of Bethany Simmelink, Calen Beck, Aaron Underwood, Savannah Coil, Halle Mizner, Cody Cleary, Faith Reinert, Ethan Wirth, Trinity Ruthstrom and Jada Eilert.
